## 1. Frontmatter (YAML)

Frontmatter appears at the top of the file between `---` markers. It's parsed as YAML and becomes `markdoc.frontmatter`.

```yaml
---
title: "My Fancy Page"
description: "One-line summary."
layout: "docs"
tags:
  - tutorial
  - markdoc
published: true
date: 2025-10-29
authors:
  - name: "Shelton"
    twitter: "@shelton"
version: 1.2
---
```

Access in content via variables or functions: e.g. `$markdoc.frontmatter.title` or `{% markdoc.frontmatter.title %}` depending on render method.

---

## 2. Core Markdown nodes

Standard Markdown nodes are supported (CommonMark).

Examples:

```markdown
# H1
## H2
### H3

Paragraph text with **bold**, *italic*, and `inline code`.

- Unordered list
  - nested item
1. Ordered list

> Block quote

![Alt text](/assets/image.png "Optional title")
[Link text](https://example.com)
```

Markdoc preserves these nodes in the AST and allows annotations and tags to be mixed in.

---

## 3. Code fences and highlighting

Use fenced code blocks with language identifiers.

```js
console.log("Hello Markdoc");
```

You can also use the `{% code %}` tag (if present in your schema) to add extra rendering options.

```markdoc
{% code lang="js" filename="example.js" lineNumbers=true %}
console.log("hello");
{% /code %}
```

---

## 4. Comments

HTML-style comments are supported. They are removed during render (when `allowComments` is true).

```markdown
<!-- This comment will not appear in the rendered output -->
```

---

## 5. Tags — basic syntax

Tags are Markdoc’s structured components. Use `{% tagName attr="value" %}` for an opening tag and `{% /tagName %}` to close.

```markdoc
{% callout type="info" %}
This is an informational callout.
{% /callout %}
```

Tags can contain Markdown and nested tags.

---

## 6. Self-closing tags

If a tag doesn’t need a body, use the self-closing syntax `/%}`.

```markdoc
{% toc /%}
{% include src="./partials/sidebar.mdoc" /%}
```

---

## 7. Inline tags

Tags can be used inline within paragraphs for small components.

Example: embedding a badge or an inline code helper.

```markdoc
Use the {% badge text="beta" /%} release for testing.
```

Be aware: inline tags must render to inline elements (span-like) in your component implementation.

---

## 8. Tag attributes (types & examples)

Attributes can be strings, numbers, booleans, arrays, objects, variables, or expressions.

Examples:

```markdoc
{% widget
  name="weather"
  version=3
  enabled=true
  coords=[37.7749, -122.4194]
  meta={ id: "w-123", source: "api" }
  tags=["weather","api"]
  primaryColor=$theme.primary
%}
```

<article>
    This is nice
</article>

<footer>
   This is nice
</footer>


- Strings — quoted or unquoted when simple: `name="x"` or `title=hello` (best to quote).
- Numbers — `count=5`
- Booleans — `visible=true`
- Arrays — `[1, 2, "three"]`
- Objects — `{ key: "value", n: 5 }`
- Variables — `$markdoc.frontmatter.title` or `$user.id`
- Expressions — `join(["a","b"], ", ")`

### Attribute precedence and evaluation

Attributes are evaluated at transform/render time. If they reference variables or functions, those must be present in the transform context or functions registry.

---

## 9. Annotations on nodes

Annotations let you attach attributes to native nodes (like headings, lists, table rows).

```markdown
# My Heading {% id="my-heading" %}
- Item 1 {% class="muted" %}
```

Annotations are written following the node content and apply to that node. They are especially useful for controlling layout (e.g., column widths for table cells).

Example for tables:

```markdoc
{% table %}
* fooo {% width="25%" %}
___
* ok
{% /table %}
```

---

## 10. Variables and context

Markdoc supports variables accessible via `$` or templating in your render layer.

**Frontmatter variables:** `$markdoc.frontmatter.<key>`

**Custom variables:** you pass them through the transform/render call.

Example usage inside content:

```markdoc
Hello, {% $user.name %}!
Current version: {% $markdoc.frontmatter.version %}
```

Or using mustache-like interpolation (depending on renderer):

```markdown
{% user.name %}
```

---

## 11. Expressions & functions

Markdoc allows functions to be executed in expressions. Common functions include `titleCase`, `if`, `equals`, `join`, `map`, `filter`, etc., depending on your registered function set.

Examples:

```markdoc
{% titleCase($markdoc.frontmatter.title) %}

{% if equals($user.role, "admin") %}
Welcome, admin!
{% else  equals($user.role, "guest") /%}
Welcome guest!
{% else /%}
Please sign in.
{% /if %}
```

You can pass expressions as attributes:

```markdoc
{% card title=titleCase($markdoc.frontmatter.title) show=equals($user.role,"admin") %}
Content...
{% /card %}
```

---

## 12. Conditionals (`if` / `elseif` / `else`)

Markdoc supports conditional tags in the schema if you register them (many projects provide an `if` tag by default).

```markdoc
{% if $user %}
Hello, {% $user.name %}!

{% else equals($role, "guest") /%}

Welcome guest!

{% else /%}
Please sign in.
{% /if %}
```

`elseif` may appear as `elsif` or be implemented as nested `if` depending on your function/tag definitions.

---


## 14. Includes & partials

Include external Markdoc files or snippets.

```markdoc
{% include src="./partials/intro.mdoc" /%}
```

`include` can be implemented to read files at build time and inject the parsed AST into the current document. This is ideal for reusing common sections (e.g., contributor guides, TOC, disclaimers).

---



## 17. Custom functions (how to register)

Functions are registered in the `functions` key of the schema or passed into `transform`.

```js
const functions = {
  titleCase: (s) => s.replace(/\w\S*/g, (t) => t.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + t.slice(1)),
  join: (arr, sep) => arr.join(sep),
  equals: (a, b) => a === b,
  formatDate: (d, fmt) => /* format logic */
};

const transformed = Markdoc.transform(ast, { functions, variables: { user } });
```

Call in Markdoc:

```markdoc
{% formatDate($markdoc.frontmatter.date, "YYYY-MM-DD") %}
```

---

## 18. Rendering pipeline (parse → transform → render)

Typical flow:

1. `Markdoc.parse(markdown)` → AST
2. `Markdoc.transform(ast, { schema, variables, functions })` → transformed AST or JSON tree ready for rendering
3. `Markdoc.renderers.react(transformed, React.createElement)` → React elements (example) OR produce HTML via custom renderer.

Example:

```js
import Markdoc from '@markdoc/markdoc';
import ReactDOMServer from 'react-dom/server';
import MyComponents from './components';

const ast = Markdoc.parse(markdown);
const transformed = Markdoc.transform(ast, { schema, variables, functions });
const content = Markdoc.renderers.react(transformed, React.createElement, { components: MyComponents });
const html = ReactDOMServer.renderToString(content);
```

---

## 19. Using Markdoc with frameworks (React / Next.js)

Example Next.js setup (app or pages):

- Parse and transform in `getStaticProps` or at build time.
- Pass `transformed` data to React rendering.

```js
// pages/docs/[slug].js
export async function getStaticProps(ctx) {
  const markdown = fs.readFileSync(`content/${ctx.params.slug}.mdoc`, 'utf8');
  const ast = Markdoc.parse(markdown);
  const transformed = Markdoc.transform(ast, { schema, variables: { /* ... */ }, functions });
  return { props: { transformed } };
}

export default function DocPage({ transformed }) {
  return (
    <article>{Markdoc.renderers.react(transformed, React.createElement, { components: MyComponents })}</article>
  );
}
```


## 20. Examples: full pages

### Example: Full feature page with many constructs

```markdoc
---
title: "Complete Example"
date: 2025-10-29
version: 2
---

# Complete Example

{% callout type="info" %}
This page demonstrates many Markdoc features in one place.
{% /callout %}

## Frontmatter Value

Title from frontmatter: {% $markdoc.frontmatter.title %}

## Table of Contents

{% toc /%}

## Inline tag and annotation

Here is an inline badge: {% badge text="alpha" /%} and a heading with an ID:
## Features {% id="features" %}

- Item A {% class="muted" %}
- Item B

## Code block

```js
console.log("This is a code sample");
```

## Conditional example

{% if equals($user.role, "admin") %}
Welcome admin: {% $user.name %}
{% else %}
Please sign in to view admin content.
{% /if %}


## Table example with annotations

{% table %}
* ok
___
* nice
{% /table %}

{% include src="./partials/footnote.mdoc" /%}


